import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    zipcodes_per_state = data.groupby('state')['zip_code'].count().reset_index()
    plt.bar(zipcodes_per_state['state'], zipcodes_per_state['zip_code'])
    plt.title('What is the distribution of zip codes across different states?', wrap=True)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))
    ax.scatter(data['longitude'], data['latitude'], alpha=0.5, color='blue')
    ax.set_xlabel('Longitude')
    ax.set_ylabel('Latitude')
    ax.set_title('What is the distribution of latitude and longitude across the dataset?')
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    top_cities = data['city'].value_counts().nlargest(10)
    plt.barh(top_cities.index, top_cities.values, color='green')
    plt.title('What is the most common city in the dataset?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Frequency')
    plt.ylabel('City')
    plt.legend([f'Most common city: {top_cities.index[0]} ({top_cities.iloc[0]:,.2f})'])
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    county = 'Gladwin'
    county_data = data[data['county'] == county]
    plt.hist(county_data['zip_code'], bins=50, color='blue')
    plt.axvline(county_data['zip_code'].median(), color='red', label='Median: {:.2f}'.format(county_data['zip_code'].median()))
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of zip codes within {} county?'.format(county), wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
